Date: Wed 10 Aug 2022 16:48 EDT
Source: Fox17 Online [edited]
https://www.fox17online.com/news/local-news/lakeshore/ottawa/9-sick-4-hospitalized-in-ottawa-county-with-e-coli-subtype


Health officials are warning Ottawa County (Michigan) residents of rising cases of _E. coli_ induced by Shiga toxin producing _E. coli_ (also called enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_ EHEC). The Ottawa County Department of Public Health (OCDPH) says they are tracking 9 EHEC cases, noting it is an unusually high number of infections compared with this time in 2021.

EHEC is described as a pathogenic subcategory of _E. coli_ that commonly arises from food-related outbreaks. Symptoms include diarrhea (often bloody), severe cramps in the stomach area, mild fever and vomiting, according to OCDPH.

County health officials tell us they are working alongside the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services (MDHHS) and the Michigan Department of Agriculture and Rural Development (MDARD) to determine if there are any links among those cases. Four of the 9 cases resulted in hospitalizations.

To prevent illness, OCDPH encourages frequent hand washing; rinsing fruits and vegetables with running water (unless the package states it is already washed); thoroughly cook meat products, avoid cross-contamination; refraining from consuming lake/pond/river/pool water, raw milk or unpasteurized drinks (e.g., fresh apple cider); and to stay home if you are unwell.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED

[The serotype of EHEC is not stated here. The prototypic strain is O157:H7. About 10% of infections can develop hemolytic uremic syndrome due to the effects of the Shiga toxin, and it is believed that antimicrobial therapy, often given empirically for presumed bacterial enteritis, can increase the risk of this potentially fatal complication.

Ottawa County, Michigan is located along Lake Michigan, west of the city of Grand Rapids. - Mod.LL

